---
import BlogPostLayout from '../../../../layouts/BlogPostLayout.astro';

const lang = 'en-us';
const post = {
  title: 'Amalfi Coast Wines',
  subtitle: 'A Journey Through the Heroic Vineyards of Tramonti and Scala',
  category: 'FOOD',
  date: 'April 22, 2026',
  readTime: '8 min',
  image: '/images/vini-costa-amalfi-hero.jpg',
  imageAlt: 'Heroic vineyards of the Amalfi Coast - Tramonti and Scala',
  path: '/en-us/blog/amalfi-coast-wines/',
};

const metaTitle = "Amalfi Coast DOC Wines: Tintore, Tramonti and Heroic Viticulture | Guide 2026";
const metaDescription = "The Costa d'Amalfi DOC between Tramonti and Scala: 200-year-old pre-phylloxera vines, native grape varieties (Tintore, Fenile, Ripoli), heroic viticulture and a guide to wine tastings.";

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/en-us/' },
  { name: 'Blog', url: '/en-us/blog/' },
  { name: 'Amalfi Coast Wines', url: '/en-us/blog/amalfi-coast-wines/' },
];

const quickInfo = [
  { label: 'DOC', value: "Costa d'Amalfi (Tramonti, Ravello, Furore)" },
  { label: 'Star grape', value: 'Tintore di Tramonti' },
  { label: 'Native whites', value: 'Fenile · Ripoli · Ginestra' },
  { label: 'Reds', value: 'Tintore · Piedirosso · Aglianico' },
  { label: 'Harvest', value: 'Late October / Early November' },
  { label: 'Pairing', value: 'Provolone del Monaco DOP' },
  { label: 'Oldest vines', value: 'Over 200 years old (pre-phylloxera)' },
  { label: 'Method', value: 'Exclusively hand-harvested' },
];

const faq = [
  {
    q: 'What does "Heroic Viticulture" mean?',
    a: 'It refers to vineyards where the slope exceeds 30%, or where vines grow on terraces or at high altitudes. On the Amalfi Coast, all work — from pruning to harvesting — must be done by hand because machinery cannot reach the terraced plots.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is the difference between coastal and mountain wines on the Amalfi Coast?',
    a: "Wines from coastal areas (Furore, Positano) tend to be more saline and sun-drenched. Those from Tramonti and Scala have more pronounced freshness and acidity, with deeper mineral notes due to the proximity of the mountains and significant day-night temperature swings.",
  },
  {
    q: 'Can you buy wines directly from the winery?',
    a: "Absolutely. In fact, it is the best way to discover small limited productions (often just a few thousand bottles) that never reach large retail distribution. Many wineries in Tramonti accept visits by appointment.",
  },
  {
    q: 'What is Tintore di Tramonti?',
    a: 'It is a unique native grape variety found nowhere else in the world, with vines that can be 150–200 years old. It survived phylloxera thanks to the volcanic and sandy soil, and produces a wine of deep, almost violet red colour with notes of wild berries and a powerful tannin.',
  },
  {
    q: "When is the harvest in the Costa d'Amalfi DOC?",
    a: "The harvest takes place between late October and early November, one of the latest in Italy. The cooler temperatures at altitude and the extended temperature variation allow the grapes to ripen slowly, developing aromatic complexity.",
  },
  {
    q: 'What are the native white grape varieties of the DOC?',
    a: 'The main native whites are Fenile, Ripoli and Ginestra — names that are extremely rare even in the Campanian wine scene. They produce wines with aromas of broom flowers, aromatic herbs and a pronounced marine salinity, very different from the more common southern Italian whites.',
  },
];

const sidebarLinks = [
  { label: 'Cetara Anchovies', href: '/en-us/blog/cetara-anchovies/' },
  { label: 'Lemon Delight', href: '/en-us/blog/lemon-delight/' },
  { label: 'Boat Tours', href: '/en-us/experiences/boat-tours/' },
  { label: 'When to visit', href: '/en-us/when-to-visit/' },
  { label: 'Getting here', href: '/en-us/getting-here/' },
];

const authorRole = 'Wine & Territory Expert · Amalfi Coast';

const relatedArticles = [
  {
    title: 'Cetara Anchovies',
    category: 'FOOD',
    date: 'April 22, 2026',
    image: '/images/alici-cetara-hero.jpg',
    imageAlt: 'Cetara Anchovies and Colatura DOP - Amalfi Coast',
    path: '/en-us/blog/cetara-anchovies/'
  },
  {
    title: 'Lemon Delight',
    category: 'FOOD',
    date: 'April 22, 2026',
    image: '/images/delizia-limone-hero.jpg',
    imageAlt: 'Delizia al Limone - the iconic dessert of the Amalfi Coast',
    path: '/en-us/blog/lemon-delight/'
  }
];
---

<BlogPostLayout
  lang={lang}
  post={post}
  metaTitle={metaTitle}
  metaDescription={metaDescription}
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  quickInfo={quickInfo}
  faq={faq}
  sidebarLinks={sidebarLinks}
  authorRole={authorRole}
  relatedArticles={relatedArticles}
>

  <!-- Intro -->
  <div>
    <p class="text-slate-600 text-xl leading-relaxed mb-6 font-light">
      When you think of the Amalfi Coast, the immediate image is the blue of the sea. But look up toward the Monti Lattari and you discover another side of the Coast: green, rugged and marked by rows of vines that defy gravity. It is here, between Tramonti and Scala, that the so-called <strong>heroic viticulture</strong> is born — where wine is not just a drink but the story of a thousand-year struggle between man and rock.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Tramonti -->
  <div>
    <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">Tramonti: The Green Lung and the Pre-Phylloxera Giants</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
      Tramonti is the land of century-old vineyards. Here the landscape changes dramatically: the air turns cool and the influence of the sea meets mountain breezes. The true peculiarity of Tramonti is the presence of <strong>Tintore</strong> vines, a native grape variety unique in the world, with enormous stocks that have reached 150 or 200 years of age.
    </p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-8">
      These plants survived phylloxera thanks to the volcanic and sandy soil. Seeing these gnarled "giants", cultivated with the traditional <strong>raggiera tramontina</strong> system — an ancient training method that creates a canopy of leaves — is an experience that moves every wine lover.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-[2rem] border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
        <span class="text-med-gold font-bold text-2xl leading-none mt-1">●</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Tintore</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">A wine of deep, almost violet red colour, with notes of wild berries and a powerful tannin that evokes the strength of the volcanic earth. Produced in just a few thousand bottles a year, it is one of the most sought-after reds in southern Italy.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Scala -->
  <div>
    <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">Scala: Elegance Among the Clouds</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
      Scala is the oldest village on the Coast and its vineyards reflect this nobility. Less extensive than those of Tramonti, the Scala rows are often nestled in small terraces among the ruins of ancient churches and noble palaces.
    </p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 text-lg leading-relaxed">
      Production here focuses on whites of extreme elegance and reds of great finesse, benefiting from a remarkable temperature swing between the warmth of the day and the cool nights of the Monti Lattari.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Native grapes -->
  <div>
    <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">The Native Grape Varieties of the Costa d'Amalfi DOC</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-8">
      Forget the classic international varieties. Here names that smell of history reign supreme.
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-8">
      <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-[2rem] border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
        <p class="text-med-gold text-[10px] font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] mb-3">White Grapes</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-600 text-sm">
          <li><strong>Fenile</strong> — white flowers and almond aromas</li>
          <li><strong>Ripoli</strong> — freshness and marine salinity</li>
          <li><strong>Ginestra</strong> — aromatic herbs and yellow flowers</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-[2rem] border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
        <p class="text-med-gold text-[10px] font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] mb-3">Red Grapes</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-600 text-sm">
          <li><strong>Tintore</strong> — power and longevity</li>
          <li><strong>Piedirosso</strong> (Per 'e Palummo) — volcanic elegance</li>
          <li><strong>Aglianico</strong> — structure and minerality</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-med-gold pl-6">
      <p class="text-slate-700 text-xl font-serif italic leading-relaxed">
        "Drinking a wine from Tramonti or Scala means sipping the history of a territory that has never accepted compromises with modernity."
      </p>
    </blockquote>
  </div>

  <!-- Where to taste -->
  <div>
    <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">Tasting Guide: Where to Go</h2>
    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-[2rem] border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead class="bg-slate-900 text-white">
          <tr>
            <th class="text-left p-5 font-serif font-bold text-med-gold">Area</th>
            <th class="text-left p-5 font-serif font-bold text-med-gold">Recommended Experience</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="bg-white">
          <tr class="border-b border-slate-100">
            <td class="p-5 font-bold text-slate-900">Tramonti</td>
            <td class="p-5 text-slate-600">Visit historic wineries to admire the pre-phylloxera vines. Many offer tastings with local cheeses and cured meats by appointment.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-5 font-bold text-slate-900">Scala</td>
            <td class="p-5 text-slate-600">Trekking through vineyards overlooking Ravello, with stops at small family farms. A unique wine-and-landscape experience in Italy.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Expert Tips -->
  <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-[2rem] shadow-xl border border-slate-100">
    <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-6">
      <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-med-gold flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M9 18h6"/><path d="M10 22h4"/><path d="M15.09 14c.18-.98.65-1.74 1.41-2.5A4.65 4.65 0 0 0 18 8 6 6 0 0 0 6 8c0 1 .23 2.23 1.5 3.5A4.61 4.61 0 0 1 8.91 14"/></svg>
      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Expert Tips</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <p class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">The Perfect Pairing</p>
        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Pair a Tramonti red (perhaps a Tintore riserva) with Provolone del Monaco DOP. The spiciness of the cheese and the structure of the wine create a legendary balance that locals have known for centuries.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">The Winery as Museum</p>
        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Some wineries in Tramonti let you walk literally beneath century-old vines. It is a vegetable cathedral: bring your camera because the light filtering through the leaves is magical, especially in the morning.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Not Just White</p>
        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Even though the Coast is seafood country, the reds from these hills are incredible with traditional mountain meats such as goat or black pig. Ask the producer for their recommendation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

</BlogPostLayout>
